    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Tall, narrow central frond arises from a small disc-like holdfast and gives off lateral spear-like branches, all in a single plane. Each lateral branch arises from a narrow base and has finely-serrated margins. Colour uniform light yellowish-brown, darkening with age.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_6800",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Large, reaching 100 cm in height, fronds about 3 cm wide.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_6801",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Chile and Southern Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u><i><u> </u></i>Namibia to Betty‘s Bay.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_6802",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Common understorey species in kelp beds,<i> </i>where it ranges from sublittoral fringe to 25 m depth. Well-known for its ability to secrete sulphuric acid to deter herbivores. When stranded on rocks burns distinctive pale shadows into rock surfaces which often attracts interest. &nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_6803",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Photosynthetic.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_6804",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Alternating generations of the large spore-producing sporophytes and small filamentous separate male and female gametophytes.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_6805",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>The large size and unusual branching pattern of fronds are good identification features.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_6806",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Anderson, RJ (1982). The life history of <i>Desmarestia firma</i> (C. Ag.) Skottsb.(Phaeophyceae, Desmarestiales). <i><i>Phycologia</i></i>, 21(3), 316-322.<br><br>Branch, G, Griffiths, CL, Branch, M & Beckley, L (2016). Two Oceans: A Guide to the Marine Life of Southern Africa (Fourth edition). Struik Nature, Cape Town. (p. 384). <br><br>Stegenga, H, Bolton, J & Anderson, R (1997). Seaweeds of the South African west coast. <i>Contributions of the Bolus Herbarium</i>, 18. (p. 175).",
